io.github.retrooper.packetevents.event.priority

Enum PacketEventPriority

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<PacketEventPriority>
      • io.github.retrooper.packetevents.event.priority.PacketEventPriority
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<PacketEventPriority>
    Deprecated.

    @Deprecated
public enum PacketEventPriority
extends java.lang.Enum<PacketEventPriority>
    Event priority enum for the new event system. The event priority counts for the whole PacketListenerAbstract and not for just one event. The priority can be specified in the PacketListenerAbstract constructor. If you don't specify a priority in the constructor, it will use the NORMAL priority.
    Since:
    1.6.9

    • Enum Constant Detail

      • LOWEST

        public static final PacketEventPriority LOWEST
        Deprecated. 
        The weakest event priority. The first to be processed(IN THE DYNAMIC EVENT SYSTEM ONLY). Use this if you need to be the first processing the event and need no power in cancelling an event or preventing an event cancellation.

      • LOW

        public static final PacketEventPriority LOW
        Deprecated. 
        A weak event priority. Second to be processed(IN THE DYNAMIC EVENT SYSTEM ONLY). Use this if you would prefer to be one of the first to process the event, but don't mind if some other listener processes before you.

      • NORMAL

        public static final PacketEventPriority NORMAL
        Deprecated. 
        Default event priority. Third to be processed(IN THE DYNAMIC EVENT SYSTEM ONLY). Use this if you don't really care/know when you process or just want to be in the middle.

      • HIGH

        public static final PacketEventPriority HIGH
        Deprecated. 
        Higher than the NORMAL event priority. Fourth to be processed(IN THE DYNAMIC EVENT SYSTEM ONLY). Use this if you want to process before the default event prioritized listeners.

      • HIGHEST

        public static final PacketEventPriority HIGHEST
        Deprecated. 
        Second most powerful event priority. Fifth to be processed(IN THE DYNAMIC EVENT SYSTEM ONLY). Use this if you prefer to be one of the last to process, but don't mind if some other listener really needs to process after you. Also use this if you prefer deciding if the event cancelled or not, but don't mind if some other listener urgently needs to decide over you. MONITOR is rarely ever recommended to use.

      • MONITOR

        public static final PacketEventPriority MONITOR
        Deprecated. 
        Most powerful event priority. Last(Sixth) to be processed(IN THE DYNAMIC EVENT SYSTEM ONLY). Use this if you urgently need to be the last to process or urgently need to be the final decider whether the event has cancelled or not. This is rarely recommended.
